In this study, S,N-CDs were prepared with one-pot microwave-assisted carbonization of ascorbic acid and thiourea in water as a green solvent (
                     Fig. 2
                     ). The suggested spectrofluorimetric approach for the quantitative analysis of the cited drugs relied on the selective quenching of S,N-CDs native fluorescence upon addition of APZ or CPH or PZH without requiring any pre-treatment processes for the first time.

The method's accuracy was verified for APZ samples by the acceptable % recovery obtained over the studied concentration range, as illustrated in Table 3
                           . The assay results for CPH and PZH by the developed method for raw material and tablet were compared with those obtained by comparison methods [73,74]. The Variance ratio F-test and the Student's t-test were statistically applied and the developed and comparison methods results exhibited no marked difference, concerning precision and accuracy, respectively (Table 3). In addition, the inter-day and intra-day precisions of the proposed method were examined and the studied drugs exhibited minimal % RSD values (<2%), verified the acceptable precision of the adopted method (Table 4
                           ).

The selectivity of the synthesized nanoprobe for the studied drugs was examined through adding different interferants such as Na+, Mg2+, K+, Ca2+, Ba2+, Pb2+, citric acid, maltose, dextrin, mannitol, and lactose, as presented in Fig. 9
                           . The concentration of all tested excipients and metal ions was 80.0 μM. It was found that these interferants had a weak impact on the reagent fluorescence, and only the studied drugs cause the fluorescence quenching, showing the satisfactory selectivity of the suggested method towards the cited drugs. The selectivity of the proposed method was also demonstrated by its capability to assess each of APZ and CPH in presence of other CNS drugs and PZH in presence of other co-administered drugs without any interference. The tolerance limits were determined based on the concentrations that result in 2 % relative error [75,76], and the obtained results verified the method's selectivity (Table 6
                           ).
